          "body": "The chapter's most theologically charged section is also its most personal. YHWH moves from third-person legislator to first-person advocate. The stranger (*ger*, 22:21) is protected by two prohibitions and grounded in one motive clause — 'for you were strangers in the land of Egypt.' Israel's national memory of powerlessness is conscripted into ethical obligation. The widow and orphan (22:22-24) receive the most explicit divine protection in the Covenant Code: if they are afflicted and cry out, YHWH says *I will surely hear their cry* (22:23). The verb — *tsaaq* — is the Exodus verb, the same cry Israel cried in Egypt (Exodus 2:23; 3:7). And YHWH's response is not passive sympathy but active wrath: 'My anger will be kindled, and I will kill you with the sword' (22:24). The oppressor's family will mirror the victims' family — his wives become widows, his children become orphans. The punishment is calibrated as exact poetic justice. The prohibition of interest-lending (22:25) and the return of the pledged cloak by nightfall (22:26-27) extend the same logic into economic relationships: the poor man's need is not a commercial opportunity; it is a claim on your mercy. 'I will hear him, for I am gracious' (22:27) — *channun*, the same attribute proclaimed at Sinai (Exodus 34:6-7) — is the bedrock. YHWH's advocacy for the poor is not policy; it is character."
