        "excerpt": "He shall pay five oxen for the ox and four sheep for the sheep.",
        "body": "The opening fifteen verses of Exodus 22 have been misread in two opposite directions: dismissed as primitive tit-for-tat legislation by critics of the Old Testament, or treated as a civil code to be directly applied today by those who collapse the Mosaic economy into contemporary jurisprudence. Both readings miss the chapter's own logic. The governing verb throughout these verses is *shalam* — to make complete, to restore to wholeness. Israel's property law is not primarily penal in its aim; it is restorative. The goal of every sanction is not to make the thief suffer proportionately but to return the victim to the position they occupied before the wrong.\n\nThe graduated penalties illuminate this. An ox stolen and slaughtered requires five-ox restitution (22:1); an ox found alive in the thief's hand requires only double (22:4). The difference is not the moral gravity of the theft — it is identical in both cases — but the economic harm to the victim. The slaughtered ox represents the loss of the animal's future: its labor, its calves, its dairy. The stolen but intact ox loses only the asset itself. Israel's law is doing economic reasoning in the service of restorative justice. This is why it anticipates modern restitution-based criminal theory more than most ancient Near Eastern law codes, which tend toward punitive fines payable to the state rather than reparation to the victim.\n\nThe custody cases of vv. 7-15 introduce the concept of oath-resolution before YHWH (22:10-11) when evidence is unavailable. This is not an escape clause for the dishonest; it is a recognition that YHWH is the ultimate witness to hidden transactions. The oath-before-YHWH functions as a theological deterrent — the person who swears falsely invites YHWH's judgment rather than his neighbor's. The system assumes a community in which YHWH's name carries weight. Douglas Stuart (*Exodus*, NAC) observes that the oath-mechanism also prevents a culture of perpetual litigation by providing a divinely sanctioned resolution when human evidence runs out.\n\nComparisons with the Code of Hammurabi (ca. 1750 BC) are instructive. Hammurabi's code imposes death for theft in many contexts where Israel's law requires restitution (compare Hammurabi §8 on ox theft). Israel's law is, paradoxically, *less* severe on property crime and *more* severe on crimes against persons. This inversion reflects a theological priority: human life bears the image of God; property does not. The Mosaic law refuses to execute people for economic crimes when restoration is possible.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shalam* (to make restitution) — the same root as *shalom* (peace, wholeness). Restitution is *shalom*-making for the victim. *Shenayim* (double) appears four times in the restitution sections (22:4, 7, 9) — always as the penalty for a convicted thief, making dishonesty self-defeating."
